sec.p:
Induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) can produce inexhaustible supplies of personalized neurons that are genetically matched to individuals with ASD or unaffected individuals [31]. CRISPR genome editing has also facilitated the generation of customized neurons with specific variants [32, 33]. iPSC-derived neurons have been used to model ASD, and these studies have consistently implicated altered synaptic function in the underlying pathophysiology of ASD, although the specific mechanisms of synaptic dysfunction vary between models [20, 32, 34–44] (Table 2). Compared to protein-coding genes, experimental perturbation of regulatory elements and non-coding RNAs are more technically difficult, and phenotypic effects may be challenging to detect or interpret [45–47]. We review recent insights into the role of non-coding and regulatory genetic variants in ASD, and we discuss future directions for using human iPSCs and genome editing to explore their functional consequences (Fig. 1). Table 2
